  "prompt": "Is battery water just the distilled water? If yes, can we use the water condensed by ACs or filtered by RO systems for inverter batteries?",
  "response": "Let me break this down for you:\n\nBattery Water (Distilled Water):\n1. Yes, battery water is essentially distilled water\n2. It should be pure water with no minerals or impurities\n3. Purpose is to maintain electrolyte level in lead-acid batteries\n\nAC Condensate Water:\n1. Not recommended for battery use\n2. Contains potential contaminants and microorganisms\n3. May have traces of metals or chemicals from AC system\n\nRO (Reverse Osmosis) Water:\n1. Generally acceptable for battery use\n2. Highly purified with minimal mineral content\n3. Close to distilled water quality\n4. Best alternative if distilled water is not readily available\n\nBest Practices:\n- Prefer commercially available distilled water\n- If using RO water, ensure it's from a well-maintained system\n- Avoid tap water or AC condensate\n- Check battery manufacturer's specific recommendations\n\nIn summary, RO water can be used as an alternative to distilled water for inverter batteries, but commercially available distilled water is still the most recommended option.",
